<DOC><DOCNO> ZF310-633-129 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 633 129.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  April 22 1991 v13 n16 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Symantec takes automation route with OnTarget project management.andO;(Software Review) (Symantec Corp. OnTarget project planningsoftware for Microsoft Windows) (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Miller, Michael J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>OnTarget, Symantec Corp's new Windows-based project managementsoftware, uses a less formal approach than sophisticated projectmanagers such as Scitor's Project Scheduler 5 and Symantec's ownTimeLine.andP;  The concepts of project management are complex andusually require considerable training even with a graphicalinterface.andP;  OnTarget is positioned between formal project managersand personal information managers.andP;  It uses a 'Time Table' with aspreadsheet-like layout and 'task bar' that indicates tasks.andP;  Theuser begins by entering task names down the first table column andoutlining subtasks.andP;  A 'Schedule Assistant' feature lets usersautomatically start tasks when the previous task is completed orlink tasks with a connecting icon.andP;  Typing a name into a Task InfoBox lets users assign responsibility for each task, and a WorkFlow window displays the relationship between various tasks.andO;OnTarget supplies a simple spreadsheet for tracking resources.andO;OnTarget sells for $399 plus $349 per additional module for LANusers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Symantec Corp. (Products).andO;Ticker:    SYMC.andO;Product:   OnTarget (Project management software).andO;Topic:     EvaluationProject Management SystemsSoftware PackagesGraphical User InterfaceWindowing.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>